SIMPLE: induce
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Induce
<hw>In*duce"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Induced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Inducing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>inducere</ets>, <ets>inductum</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in +
<ets>ducere</ets> to lead. See <er>Duke</er>, and cf.
<er>Induct</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To lead in; to introduce.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The poet may be seen <qex>inducing</qex> his personages in the
first Iliad.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 755 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw on; to overspread.</def> <mark>[A
Latinism]</mark> <rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To lead on; to influence; to prevail on; to incite;
to persuade; to move by persuasion or influence.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is not obliged by your offer to do it, . . . though he may be
<qex>induced</qex>, persuaded, prevailed upon, tempted.</q>
<rj><qau>Paley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let not the covetous desire of growing rich <qex>induce</qex> you
to ruin your reputation.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To bring on; to effect; to cause; <as>as, a fever
<ex>induced</ex> by fatigue or exposure; anaphylactic shock
<ex>induced</ex> by exposure to a allergen</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sour things <qex>induces</qex> a contraction in the nerves.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>To produce, or cause, by
proximity without contact or transmission, as a particular electric or
magnetic condition in a body, by the approach of another body in an
opposite electric or magnetic state.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>To generalize or conclude as an
inference from all the particulars; -- the opposite of
<contr>deduce</contr>.</def></p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Genetics, Biochemistry)</fld> <def>To cause the
expression of (a gene or gene product) by affecting a transcription
control element on the genome, either by inhibiting a negative control
or by activating a positive control; to derepress; <as>as, lactose
<ex>induces</ex> the production of beta-galactosidase in <spn>Eschericia
coli</spn>.</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To move; instigate; urge; impel; incite; press;
influence; actuate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>induced</ent>⟦br⟧
